<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence submitted by Claire Lucas, on behalf of Cambridge Association for Women in Science and Engineering (Cambridge AWiSE) (WSC033)</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Cambridge Association for Women</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> in Science and Engineering (Cambridge </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">AWiSE</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">) (WSC033)</span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 31.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps">Summary</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Cambridge </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">AWiSE</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">provides </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">support for women trained and working in Scien</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ce, Technology, Engineering, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Mathematic</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">s and Medicine. As such, the subject of this i</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">nquiry is of particular interest to the organisation.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">We put the Select Committee’s questions to a group of attendees at a re</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">cent Cambridge </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">AWiSE</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> event, and asked for their responses. These are summarised as follows, and more detail is provided later.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The number of women in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">STEM careers declines further up the career ladder, due to the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">pressure of balancing family and work commi</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">tments, the difficulties surrounding c</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">areer breaks, financial factors, a culture of exclusion, and the image of women scientists as portrayed in the media and film. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">When women leave STEM careers, they transition into a wide range of alternative careers. T</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">hese fall into the following categories: people-oriented, applied research, and positions offering either greater job security, or more flexibility.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The consequences of women leaving STEM careers may be felt by the women themselves (loss of specialist skil</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ls, steep learning-curve, loss of confidence); by the STEM employer (reduced diversity and lack of female role-models); and by the new employer (more positive, in terms of additional skills being brought to the workplace)</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Employers could do more to retain</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> women scientists, including encouraging and supporting career progression, and offering job security, flexibility and equal pay. A number of examples of good practice were identified.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The government could encourage the retention of women in STEM careers i</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">n a number of ways, including introducing legislation, policy and programmes, and supporting organisations and programmes for women in STEM. In addition, the government should work towards changing cultural attitudes towards working mothers and part-time e</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">mployees, and could set an example by including more women in high-profile positions itself.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 31.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps">Introduction</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Cambridge </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">AWiSE</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-weight:normal"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">was originally set up in 1994 as a local branch of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">AWiSE</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">. It had an active programme of events, and was primarily academic in focus. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The organisation</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> was expanded in 2004 to provide greater local support and networking opportunities for women in SET in both industry and academia in Cambridgeshire and beyond. Cambridge </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">AWiSE</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> is a voluntary organisation run by a Steering Group</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> and a paid</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> coordinator</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">; membership currently stands at about 100 members, and the events programme for 2013-14 includes around 15 events.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> Events are open to non-members as well as members.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The Select Committee’s Inquiry into Women in STEM Careers focuses on one of C</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ambridge </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">AWiSE’s</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> core concerns, hence our interest in submitting this evidence.</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 31.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps">Methodology</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">We held a networking event on July 10</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:7.33pt; vertical-align:super"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">2013</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, and asked the attendees to consider the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">four </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">questions </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">at the heart of the inquiry. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">These were adapted slightly so as </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">to include non-academic careers and employers. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The following paragraphs provide a summary of the responses received.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt"><br style="page-break-before:always; clear:both" /></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 31.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps">Why do numbers of women in STEM academic careers decline further up the career ladder?</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps">&#xa0;</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">4a. P</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">ressure of balancing family and work commitments. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">As women progress in STEM careers, the responsibilities diversify (research, teaching, clinical, administration, committees, etc.) and increase, limiting the flexibility and</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> amount of time available for fa</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">mily commitments. The lack of part-time positions, flexible working, or job</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">sharing positions was a key factor that affects the ability of women to progress in STEM careers. When flexible work arrangements do exist, they are not fully considered in the wor</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">k timetables. Networking events often occur after work hours, conflicting with family commitments. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">4b. Career breaks</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Career breaks for maternity leave and other family responsibilities tend to limit an individual’s publication rate, which affects tenure r</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">eviews and grant applications. Also, during a career break, it is difficult to keep track of the developments and contacts in the individual’s STEM field of expertise. If the career break takes place during a grant period, then it could negatively affect t</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">he annual performance on the grant and the ability to obtain new research grants, especially in large multi-organizational ones.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">4c. Monetary factors </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The effort put into careers by women can be less financially rewarded than for men. Due to the lack of </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">positions available for progression in STEM careers and the high level of competition for those positions, women may decide to take a more secure position outside of STEM careers. Financial and job insecurity due to short-term postdoctoral contracts is pro</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">blematic as child care requires a permanent income. Also, if both carers are working, then finding affordable, reliable child care is another issue.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">4d. Culture of exclusion</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">A few comments highlighted the established network amongst male colleagues and the</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> culture of exclusion for women in some STEM careers. It was mentioned that perhaps women communicate differently from men and may have to learn the established hierarchical thinking and power structure.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">4e. Image of women scientists in </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">media</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic"> and the a</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">rts</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Responses pointed to the lack of women role models in higher levels of STEM careers and suggested more proactive mentoring programs to encourage young females who are interested in STEM. However, these role models need to be positive ones as some estab</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">lished female workers, classified with “Queen Bee syndrome”, make it more difficult for other females due to their own difficult experience obtaining their position.</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 31.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps">When women leave academia, what careers do they transition into? What are the consequences</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps"> of scientifically trained women applying their skills in different employment sectors?</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">5a. New careers </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">When women leave STEM positions, they transition into a diversity of other positions. One category is </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">people-oriented positions, including teaching, public engagement, science outreach, administration, helpline management, career advising, child-care or house-wife positions. Another is applied research positions, including industrial research roles, lab ma</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">nagement, technician positions, sales and marketing. Others move into careers with more financial security, such as </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">project management, patent law, publishing, politics, accounting, political lobbying and advising as well as scientific or management consul</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ting. Finally, women sometimes choose careers with more flexibility and opportunities by transitioning to self-employment, entrepreneurship, private consultancy, scientific writing, and interim roles such as maternity cover positions.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">5b. Consequences</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Thes</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">e are three-fold; the transition affects the individual, the STEM career workplaces and the alternative employment </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">positions. The</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> new employers receive scientifically trained employees who tend to be skilled in some or all of the following: problem-solving</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, analysis, team-building, leadership, public-speaking, management, understanding of scientific methods and personnel. However, in leaving STEM careers, these employees may lose their skills that are specific to their field of expertise and encounter reduc</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ed opportunities for applying their specific talents, training and experiences in their new roles. The transition may require a fast learning-curve in an unfamiliar work environment, resulting in less confident employees, lower qualified positions, and low</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">er salaries for these employees. For STEM career workplaces, the transition contributes to a distinct lack of diversity and female role models in top STEM positions.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 31.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps">What should universities and the higher education sector do to retain women graduates and</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps"> PhD students in academic careers? Are there examples of good practice?</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">6a. Support for career progression</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Employers should provide women graduates and PhD students with strong encouragement and support for career progression through effective mentoring an</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">d personal development, enabling them to build on qualifications and technical experience to be able to move into new roles within an organisation. Many women would like to have more on-the-job coaching and training, for example in people management in ord</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">er to have the possibility of progressing into management roles that use and extend their technical knowledge. Transferable skills developed during degree and postgraduate work, such as project management, need to be better recognised and valued by employe</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">rs so that women can be encouraged to apply for senior roles and eventual progression onto board positions. More senior technically-trained women in an organisation provide role models for retention of women graduate students. </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">6b. Flexibility</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Many women g</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">raduates and PhD students wish to remain or progress in technically oriented employment but with flexibility for part-time working and family commitments. These positions need to be more readily available and better valued in an organisation. Longer-term c</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ontracts for new PhD graduates in research roles would provide better job stability and security to develop and progress a career. Employers need to provide better support for access to child-care, job-sharing, flexible and phased return to work and option</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">s for working from home to accommodate caring responsibilities.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">6c. Financial factors</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">It goes without saying that employers must establish equal pay for equal positions, and pay postgraduate students a living wage equivalent to their skill level.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">6d. Examp</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">les of good practice</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Glasgow Veterinary School and </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Boehringer</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Ingelheim</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> were cited as examples of good practice. In addition, the </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Wellcome</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> Trust offers fellowships targeting career breaks, and has local childcare </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">facilities at its campus near Cambridge. Th</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">e Daphne Jackson Trust was also highlighted for its fellowships (though not an employer as such)      </span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 31.25pt; padding-left:4.75pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-variant:small-caps">What role should the Government have in encouraging the retention of women in academic STEM careers? </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">7a. Legislation </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Legislation could be introduced to limit the use of short term contracts, and/or require women's participation in management roles (e.g. quotas).  The government could also set an example by making more women visible in senior ministerial and civil service</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> positions (offering realistic female role models), and advocating, perhaps through a media campaign, retention and diversity as economic drivers (research shows mixed teams are more productive than single sex teams). </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">7b. Policy</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">The Government could</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> adopt and promote </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">more </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">policies and programmes around childcare and parenting, in the form of subsidised childcare (not only for early years), tax relief, or child care loans, funding for childcare at conferences, and improving the system for paternity le</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">ave and fathers' time off. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">7c. Funding</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">Support, through funding and/or other means, </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">should be provided </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">for organisations and programmes that support women in STEM. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">These </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">could</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> include Women in STEM associations (like </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">AWiSE</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">), mentoring</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> programmes</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">, person</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">al development training, specialised careers advice, and support for career breaks and training. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">7d. </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Changing a</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">ttitudes</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">It is important that the Government works to change negative attitudes towards working mothers and part-time working (for both men and</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt"> women), and promotes the value society holds for both men and women in family life.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:108%; margin:0pt 0pt 8pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">August 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>